    <p> As promised last time, there is finally a report about my New Year's Eve and where I was probably looking at the world's largest New Year's Eve. </p>
    <p> During my time in Ireland, I started to think about my personal New Year's Festival in Australia. I stumbled across one <a title="&Ouml;ffnet Liste mit Schiffen im neuen Fenster" href="https://www.sailaustralia.com.au/" target="_blank"> website </a> which I have a list of all bookable ships for New Year's Eve. At that time I decided that it would probably be a cool idea to spend New Year's Eve a boat and enjoy the fireworks in the front row. </p>
    <p> But then I saw the prices for such a trip. They were between $ 300 and $ 800 (approx. 650 &euro;) I decided to wait a little. But I had already put a favorite right. The Emerald Star. </p>
    <p> I had postponed the decision whether I treat myself to this now. A few days before New Year's Eve, I found the official website for the Sydney New Year's Eve of fireworks with a little research. When I browse it, I realized how huge this fireworks will be and that it was even 2 fireworks. One at 9 p.m. for families with children and of course the big one at midnight. In the end, I decided to celebrate my New Year's Eve on a ship. </p>
  </div>
</div><div class="row margin-bottom-10">
  <div class="col-md-5 visible-sm visible-xs margin-bottom-10">
    <img class="img-bordered img-responsive img-center" src="{{ site.url }}/assets/img/blog/auszeit/small/20130202-153139.jpg" alt="Delicious fish in the Sealife Aquarium Darling Harbor">
