  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> First we drove out very comfortably from the Darling Harbor and then west away from opera and Harbor Bridge to see the sunset there. This was even more beautiful than usual. After that, we slowly made our way so that we are on time for the first fireworks in the agreed place. On the way there I was involved in an interesting conversation, about God and the world by 2 older men. When talking, a Kelner with different snacks came by regular intervals. These were excellent. </p>
    <p> A few minutes before the start of the first fireworks, we were finally in our position. I can tell you it was really the first row. To be precise not just the first row but in the middle of the fireworks. Immediately in front of us was one of the 7 shock forms next to it with the opera with the skyline in the background and of course with full view of the Harbor Bridge. Behind the ship there were 3 other platforms of which the fireworks were started. </p>
    <p> The fireworks started punctually at 9 p.m. as planned. It was really breathtakingly beautiful. Especially since the ship was in an almost perfect place. Unfortunately, the wind was a little stronger at the time, which pressed us out of the direction and the skipper had some to do with the ship. We a great view of the fireworks. <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=14FWIvAmVWQ" target="_blank"> Here is my recording on YouTube. </a></p>
  </div>
</div><div class="row margin-bottom-10">
  <div class="col-md-12">
    <p> After the fireworks were over and the area around the fireworks were released, some of the ships switched on their jewelry lighting and lined up in the light parade. Our ship also took part in this parade. We had a yellow lighting with small flashing birds on the side. </p>
    <p> In the meantime, the crew had built up a real delicacle buffet on the lower deck. With pretty much everything you can wish for. From Indian curry to seafood to melon ham. I have to mention it again how Lcker the food was. Then I got a decent drink (Whiskey Cola) and sat on the open aft deck. There I spent the rest of the time between the fireworks and enjoyed the view of Sydney and the thousands of ships. </p>
  </div>
</div><div class="row margin-bottom-10">
  <div class="col-md-5 visible-sm visible-xs margin-bottom-10">
    <img class="img-bordered img-responsive img-center" alt="Sailboat adorned with pink fairy lights and the word Embrace on the side" src="{{ site.url }}/assets/img/blog/auszeit/small/20130202-153443.jpg">
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-7">
    <p> We turned a big round through the harbor and then countless around one of the fireworks position before we went back to the same position where we were also for the fireworks. This time the wind was completely different and the boat was calm. </p>
    <p> The fireworks started slowly a few seconds before midnight. First the last seconds of the old year were counted down and at midnight the city literally exploded with fireworks and light. It was an absolute dream. I have already seen some fireworks but something like that was adjusted and synchronized fireworks was also new to me. Just wow !! <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7wYF-JkswK4" target="_blank"> Here is my recording on YouTube. </a></p>
    <p> It took almost 13 minutes and even included some of the high -rise buildings in the city center. Unfortunately, after a few minutes, something went wrong on the shooting platform right in front of us, because from there no fireworks were suddenly shot down while everyone else was always fired heavily. But they got the problem again after about a minute and fired up again. The bridge was also really nice with fireworks. Even a curtain from golden rain went down from the bridge. </p>
    <p> I have to say it again it was just wow !! </p>
  </div>
